I&#x27;ve been working on library that creates a queryable structure for trees like this. I prefer writing normal JS than to having some query language for it.<p><pre><code>  var obj = minim.toElement({
    a: 1,
    b: [
      {
        c: 1,
        d: 2,
        e: [ { f: 5 } ],
        f: 6
      }
    ]
  });

  // Results are [5, 6]
  var results = obj.find(function(value, key) {
    return key.equals(&#x27;f&#x27;);
  });
</code></pre>
See <a href="https://github.com/refractproject/minim" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/refractproject/minim</a>

It always feels like we keep reinventing Lisp. You could do something like:<p><pre><code>  [&#x27;contains?&#x27;, [&#x27;list&#x27;, 1, 2, 3], 1]
</code></pre>
Instead of:<p><pre><code>  {
    $contain: {
      foo: 1
    }
  }, {
    foo: [ 1, 2, 3 ]
  }</code></pre>
